The swapping perspectives thing is an interesting way to handle it, but I feel like if you're doing it second person style where the reader is always the "You" then you might want to try removing the character's dialogue whenever it's their POV. Like, both characters keep talking to each other in regular conversation, so it doesn't seem necessary to keep swapping second-person perspective. Maybe whenever you're the frog, for example, you can do "You say [general gist]" rather than full dialogue. It might make getting into the characters' heads a little easier when you think of your own context for what they're saying.

But it has potential behind it, and having her be a frog is a welcome change of pace. Hope you keep working at it.

Tabletop-Anon dog update.

Outside of my mother's house, nearly three miles north, lies an old shack that has grown decrepit over the years. Siding torn off, windows shattered, parts of it burned.

I hadn't ever seen it before today, so seeing it in the middle of the forest with no lead-up was scary. Faint whimpering, almost unheard was coming from the inside. I kicked the rotten door down and found the puppy. The small Boston Terrier, the runt of her litter, had been trying to keep warm under old tattered rags and burnt furniture.

She's safe now though, sleeping on the heater vent with piles of blankets over her.

Fuck the winter man, fuck it to high heaven.
TT-Anon out.

So we move in, and around two days after one of the neighbors decides to have a yard sale of their long moved away son's stuff. Dick move, I know. Oh yeah, I should mention they were all Archie Sonic the Hedgehog comics. And I was psyched the fuck out because to me Sonic Adventure on the Dreamcast was the dopest shit at the moment.
So I hand that old lady a fiver, and then run down the block back to my house to read them once I realize someone else had already swooped on his video games. At first it seemed like an incoherent collection; missed issues in between them, and a couple side issues.
